      "id":"stage/2013/nov/03/billy-the-girl-review",
      "sectionId":"stage",
      "sectionName":"Stage",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-11-03T12:32:00Z",
      "webTitle":"Billy the Girl – review",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/stage/2013/nov/03/billy-the-girl-review",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/stage/2013/nov/03/billy-the-girl-review",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"32",
        "trailText":"<p>With poignancy and humour, this three-hander explores – but fails to fully capture – a return to life after prison, writes <strong>Andrew Dickson</strong></p>",
        "headline":"Billy the Girl – review",
        "body":"<p>You're just out of jail. You've changed. But the world has changed, too, and nothing is quite where you expect it to be. Your relatives aren't overjoyed. You wonder what they're really thinking. What if they don't want you to be there? What if they never have?</p><p>For three decades, the <a href=\"http://www.cleanbreak.org.uk/mission\" title=\"\">Clean Break theatre company</a> have paired some of the most <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/stage/2010/nov/08/clean-break-women-prison-theatre\" title=\"\">exciting female writers</a> around – among them Lucy Kirkwood and Rebecca Lenkiewicz – with women who are in the criminal justice system. Katie Hims' new three-hander, distilled from residencies at HMP Holloway and HMP <a href=\"http://www.justice.gov.uk/contacts/prison-finder/askham-grange\" title=\"\">Askham Grange</a>, suggests that, for many who've been released, returning to their old lives and trying to make them new is the biggest trial of all.</p><p>Here, it's Billy who has come home. She's hectic with good intentions (\"My new approach,\" she beams, clutching a pineapple, \"my new, like, positive approach\"), but Ingrid, her mother, is dubious. Besides, Ingrid has other things on her mind: her new man Eddie, who looks like <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bJWD6_5aQDQ\" title=\"\">Patrick Swayze</a> with a pigtail and earns his living hosting seances. Billy's teenage sister, Amber, has the voice of an angel, but what is she really doing when she claims to be at choir practice? And then there's a wedding, which must be kept secret. Billy herself isn't even allowed inside the house, so it's in front of an elderly caravan parked in the back garden (a finely conceived <a href=\"http://www.cleanbreak.org.uk/productions/billy-girl\" title=\"\">dingy design</a> by Joanna Scotcher) that battle lines are redrawn and old wounds reopened.</p><p>Agonising though this triangle is – and often it's agonisingly funny – Hims' hour-and-a-half play seems somehow trapped in its premise, and, like the caravan, you begin to wish it would roam further. There are heavy hints of what has happened to Billy's stepfather (a Thermos of whose ashes gaze at us balefully throughout), and the final twist is awkward; you often sense the script grazing emotional truth without managing to make sustained contact.</p><p>But there are good things here, not least sprightly performances from Danusia Samal and Naomi Ackie as sisters who discover a skew-whiff complicity with each other. It is the only play in English drama I can think of to explore the confessional uses of a bear costume. And in Christine Entwisle's Ingrid – a study in phosphorescent makeup and hazy self-delusion (\"The dead are with us always,\" she coos, \"that's what Eddie says\") – it has a character who would look at home in a Cumbrian version of Tennessee Williams. Funny though Billy the Girl is, its most lasting insight is a sad one: that you don't have to be in prison to be trapped.</p><p>• Did you catch this show – or any other recently? Tell us about it using #gdnreview</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/421552280|2013-11-05T11:03:51Z|320ed0721a09a35729709ed9de3333251dfe610b -->",
