      "id":"stage/2013/nov/03/national-dance-company-wales-review",
      "sectionId":"stage",
      "sectionName":"Stage",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-11-03T12:26:00Z",
      "webTitle":"National Dance Company Wales – review",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/stage/2013/nov/03/national-dance-company-wales-review",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/stage/2013/nov/03/national-dance-company-wales-review",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"32",
        "trailText":"<p>With its violent relationships, Diaghilev's Les Noces still has the power to disturb, writes <strong>Judith Mackrell</strong></p>",
        "headline":"National Dance Company Wales – review",
        "body":"<p>In the late 1980s, when <a href=\"http://www.preljocaj.org/menu.php?lang=en&amp;m=1&amp;a=1\" title=\"\">Angelin Preljocaj</a> first began rewriting the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sergei_Diaghilev\" title=\"\">Diaghilev</a> repertory, his interpretations of those revered classics appeared provocative and strange. A quarter of a century on, <a href=\"http://www.ndcwales.co.uk/en\" title=\"\">NDCW</a>'s revival of Les Noces still has the power to disturb.</p><p>Preljocaj's version is cast for five soon-to-be-married couples. The violence implicit in their relationships, and in the thrilling clamour of Stravinsky's score, is embodied in the hurtling jumps and falls that break through the hard-edged patterns of Preljocaj's choreography. While the bride in the 1923 <a href=\"http://www.roh.org.uk/productions/les-noces-by-bronislava-nijinska\" title=\"\">original</a> feared marriage as a kind of death, here the couples' emotions are a more ambivalent mix of lust, fantasy and fear. Brilliantly, Preljocaj projects all these on to the five bridal mannequins who are tossed in and among the dancers, caressed and manhandled with intensifying hatred and contempt. NDCW serve the choreography well, attentive to every nuance, diving into it fearlessly. For a small company, they're impressive in the ambition of their repertory.</p><p>Virtual Descent, by company member Eleesha Drennan, may feel overwhelmed by its grandiose theme (a future world in which mankind fights to recover its humanity). But the black-clad dancers shifting through golden light look handsome, and the live performance of <a href=\"http://www.markbowden.net/\" title=\"\">Mark Bowden</a>'s percussion concerto is an exceptional and absorbing pleasure.</p><p>Closing the programme is <a href=\"http://stephenpetronio.com/\" title=\"\">Stephen Petronio</a>'s Water Stories. Petronio has developed a close working relationship with the Cardiff company, and for this piece has taken inspiration from the Welsh countryside. Scenes of coastline, rivers and lakes are projected on stage, and the water imagery is embodied in the choreography's eddies and swirls of dance. Costumed in postmodern Greek tunics, the dancers look wonderful, like new age nymphs of the landscape.</p><p>• Did you catch this show – or any other recently? Tell us about it using #gdnreview</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/421551514|2013-11-05T11:03:51Z|f331723485be5e267346569115b2e3d0e1bb77f4 -->",
