      "id":"stage/2013/oct/31/comedy-exclusive-isy-suttie-bridget-christie-channel-4-blap",
      "sectionId":"stage",
      "sectionName":"Stage",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-31T10:09:00Z",
      "webTitle":"Exclusive clips: Isy Suttie, Bridget Christie and more go blap!",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/stage/2013/oct/31/comedy-exclusive-isy-suttie-bridget-christie-channel-4-blap",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/stage/2013/oct/31/comedy-exclusive-isy-suttie-bridget-christie-channel-4-blap",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"<p>Watch a brand-new Channel 4 online comedy series starring Isy Suttie, Thom Tuck, Josie Long and a firmament of other comedy stars. <strong>Brian Logan</strong> explains all</p>",
        "headline":"Exclusive clips: Isy Suttie, Bridget Christie and more go blap!",
        "body":"<p><a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YvIzyWJI8EQ\" title=\"\">Reading on mobile? Click to view</a></p><p>\"Does that word have a rude origin?\" asks Peep Show star <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/2012/jun/03/isy-suttie-peep-show-interview\" title=\"\">Isy Suttie</a>. \"There's a word that comes from the sound of a dick hitting something. Is that blap?\" Channel 4's new comedy boss <a href=\"http://www.channel4.com/info/press/news/phil-clarke-named-as-channel-4s-new-head-of-comedy\" title=\"\">Phil Clarke</a> isn't sure either:  \"I was told it was a made-up word, and to 'stop asking questions, old man!'\" Comedian <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John-Luke_Roberts\" title=\"\">John Luke-Roberts</a> just thinks it's a \"satisfying word to say\".</p><p>Whatever its origins, it's somewhat clearer what a \"blap\" actually is: today, the Guardian makes exclusively available online a new batch of <a href=\"http://comedyblaps.channel4.com/\" title=\"\">Channel 4's Comedy Blaps</a>. A blap, says Clarke, is \"a pilot for a pilot\", a five- or six-minute shock of comedy, commissioned by the channel to road-test new talent, and broadcast online. Sixteen mini-series of blaps have been created in the last two years, clocking up 2.6m views between them. They've featured talent including Aussie comic <a href=\"http://vimeo.com/69739558\" title=\"\">Claudia O'Doherty</a> and Irish hip-hop hoodlums <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dSorEwCM7Fw&amp;list=PL179EDAD1ACB1B501&amp;index=32\" title=\"\">The Rubberbandits</a>, award-winning sexy clown <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XfONJQ7DudQ&amp;list=PL179EDAD1ACB1B501&amp;index=13\" title=\"\">Dr Brown</a> and the animators behind scuzzy cartoon <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Hr3eT3kZz4A&amp;list=PL179EDAD1ACB1B501&amp;index=20\" title=\"\">Modern Toss</a>.</p><p>Today's release features the stars of the <a href=\"http://noblefailure.org/\" title=\"\">Alternative Comedy Memorial Society</a>, a regular night launched in 2011 by John-Luke Roberts and <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/stage/2011/aug/28/thom-tuck-review\" title=\"\">Thom Tuck</a> to showcase the best in indie comedy. Rather than transfer that live event directly to the screen, Roberts has written a part-sketch, part-sitcom format, which finds the 10 ACMS comics holding a board meeting in a building that's being consumed by fire. The four webisodes (my apologies for the word) find <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/2013/aug/28/bridget-christie-edinburgh-comedy-award\" title=\"\">Edinburgh comedy award champ Bridget Christie</a> dreaming up hare-brained schemes to escape the flames, <a href=\"http://www.josielong.com/\" title=\"\">Josie Long</a> being executed by the grim reaper, and Suttie largely confined to the inside of a cardboard box.</p><p>They're great fun, and give a glimpse of what this collective of freewheeling comics could do with a full 30 minutes of TV. But will they get that far? So far, several blaps have graduated to pilot, but none to full series – except <a href=\"http://www.comedy.co.uk/news/story/000001128/\" title=\"\">Nick Helm's Uncle</a>, which was finally turned down by Channel 4, then picked up by the BBC. The danger, as comedy commissioner Clarke is aware, is that the blap format starts to look like a ghetto for innovative new talent, running on parallel tracks to the channel's main output.</p><p>Clarke is adamant that won't happen: \"The blap has always got to be the first step on a ladder.\" What's exciting about the scheme, he says, is that blaps allow more talent in front of the camera. \"We can make so few full pilots here,\" he says: \"between six and 10 every year if we absolutely go hell-for-leather. And that's a bottleneck.\" Blaps are cheaper than pilots, and need less oversight. They widen the gene pool. And they give more talent the chance, not just to pitch their ideas, but to bring them to life. \"The advantage of doing a blap is that [the potential show] is in front of you. You can go back and look at it all the time. A script has to exist in your imagination, and you might imagine something completely different. But a blap is a tangible proposition.\"</p><p>So how does the talent feel? Are blaps another unnecessary hoop to jump through – or a new and improved opportunity to get work on (or near) TV? Both, says John-Luke Roberts – but he's inclined to be positive. \"As a comedian, you're constantly trying out stuff in front of audiences, getting feedback, finding out what works and what doesn't. If you can do that for broadcast too, without it being massively high-stakes, that's a good development.\"</p><p>It's certainly preferable to the old system. \"Most of my work for TV,\" says Roberts, \"has been putting forward an idea, getting somewhere with the idea, working on the idea for a long time, and then people going, 'no, we don't like it,' for no rational reason.\" Suttie agrees: \"Ideas get talked and talked and talked over, and you just want to shoot someone. Whereas,\" she adds, \"the minute you've got a concrete thing you can show people, you're in a much better position.\"</p><p>What blaps do too is democratise the decision-making process, at least a little – in that commissioning editors may find online popularity and Twitter buzz a persuasive reason to take a blap to the next level. There's certainly an audience for this new medium: bite-sized, web-based comedy is a boom phenomenon. The BBC has its <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p01bhx0w/episodes/guide\" title=\"\">Feed My Funny</a> strand, available on iPlayer. YouTube recently ran its inaugural <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/stage/2013/may/20/youtube-comedy-week-sarah-silverman\" title=\"\">Comedy Week</a>, and this month saw the launch of new online comedy network/production company <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/user/TheWagonComedy\" title=\"\">The Wagon</a>, which numbers Jack Whitehall among its clients.</p><p>So is the five-minute Comedy Blap really just \"a pilot for a pilot\" – or is it an end in itself? Roberts certainly didn't consider the ACMS blap as a mere dry run. \"If there's one thing you learn in this business, it's that we probably won't get a chance to make this again. So we made it as good as we can for this format and this occasion.\" But he – and Suttie – aren't ready yet for a world in which we all consume our screen comedy in five-minute chunks. (Or to put it another way: they do want a series.) Back at Channel 4, Clarke is more relaxed about the 21st-century format free-for-all. \"These things are changing fast as technology changes,\" he says, cheerfully. \"But there's no reason to panic, because people still want content. As long as it's about how funny or clever or engaging the comedy is, how it's viewed is academic.\"</p><h2><strong>Watch the rest of the episodes here: </strong></h2><p><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/stage/2013/oct/31/comedy-blap-episode-2\">Episode 2: The Bloody First Floor Is on Fire, Guys!</a></p><p><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/stage/2013/oct/31/alternative-comedy-memorial-society-episode-3\">Episode 3: Well, I'll Be, The Fire's on the Second Floor (Third, if You Are American)</a></p><p><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/stage/2013/oct/31/alternative-comedy-memorial-society-episode-4\">Episode 4: Well, Great, the Bloody Third Floor Is on Fire Now</a></p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/421304185|2013-11-05T11:03:51Z|1b590f54e7d8789b716a3d094d9c8f365079fab6 -->",
